# Pipedream workflow authoring

## When this applies

Trigger on any of:

- "create a new Pipedream workflow"
- "port / clone / refactor a workflow under `exported_workflows/`"
- "add a step to workflow X"
- "scaffold a workflow that does Y"
- the user mentions a `p_xxx` workflow id, `defineComponent`, `steps.foo.$return_value`, `$.export`, `$.flow.delay/suspend`, `$.respond`, or `$.service.db`

If the user is migrating workflows OFF Pipedream onto the self-hosted automation-platform, fall through to that project's own porter (`scripts/migrate-workflow.js` in `automation-platform/`); this skill is for staying inside Pipedream.

## On-disk shape (mirrors `scripts/refresh-exports.mjs` output)

```
exported_workflows/<Project>/<WorkflowName>/
  workflow_definition.json    ← full API payload (triggers, steps, props, secrets)
  <stepName>.js               ← node code-cell steps
  <stepName>.py               ← python code-cell steps
  <stepName>_action.json      ← prebuilt component steps (no inline code)
```

**Rules when generating files:**
1. One step ⇒ one file. File basename = step's `namespace` (preferred) or `name`.
2. `workflow_definition.json` is the source of truth for ordering, props, secrets, and trigger config — code files are reconstructions of `step.savedComponent.code`.
3. Sanitise step names with `[<>:"/\\|?*]` → `-` and whitespace → `_`.

## Step contract — Node (the 95% case)

```js
export default defineComponent({
  // OPTIONAL: typed props the step needs (auth, user input, upstream data)
  props: {
    notion: { type: "app", app: "notion" },                    // connected account
    databaseId: { type: "string", label: "Notion database id" },
    rowsPerPage: { type: "integer", default: 50, optional: true },
  },
  // run() receives:
  //   steps : map of prior steps' return values, indexed by step name
  //   $     : the Pipedream helper (see below)
  async run({ steps, $ }) {
    const upstream = steps.retrieveTeamMember.$return_value;     // chain pattern
    // ...
    return { ok: true, data };                                   // becomes $return_value
  },
});
```

### `$` helper — what's actually available

| API | Purpose |
|---|---|
| `$.export(key, value)` | Attach a labelled value to the run timeline (visible in Pipedream UI logs). NOT the same as `return`. |
| `$.respond({status, headers, body})` | For HTTP-trigger workflows: send the HTTP response. Required when the trigger is `HttpInterface` and you want to control the response. |
| `$.flow.exit("reason")` | Terminate the workflow run early (success). |
| `$.flow.delay(ms)` | Pause and resume after `ms`. Returns a sentinel — **do not** `return` the result; just call it. |
| `$.flow.suspend({timeout})` then later `$.flow.resume(callbackId, payload)` | Long-running waits keyed by callback id. |
| `$.service.db.get/set(key)` | Per-workflow KV store (string-keyed JSON). Survives between runs. Fast. |
| `$.send.http({...})`, `$.send.email({...})`, `$.send.sse(...)` | Pipedream-managed delivery primitives. Prefer official SDKs (axios/googleapis) for non-Pipedream destinations. |

### Trigger types (in `workflow_definition.json` `triggers[].type`)

| `type` | When to use | Notes |
|---|---|---|
| `HttpInterface` | Inbound webhook | Pipedream gives the URL. Use `$.respond` to shape the response. |
| `Timer` | Cron / interval | `triggers[0].cron_string` or `triggers[0].interval_seconds`. |
| `EventSource` | Component-keyed event stream (Slack message, new Notion page, etc.) | `triggers[0].savedComponent.key` (e.g. `slack-new-message-in-channels`). |
| `Email` | Inbound email-to-workflow | Generates a unique `*@pipedream.net` address. |

A workflow has exactly one trigger. To "fan in" multiple triggers, build N workflows that share a common downstream workflow via HTTP.

## Common patterns from this codebase

These are taken from real workflows under `./exported_workflows/`. Match this style when scaffolding new ones.

### Pattern: Notion query → conditional → action

```js
// retrieveTeamMember.js
export default defineComponent({
  props: { notion: { type: "app", app: "notion" } },
  async run({ steps, $ }) {
    const rows = steps.retrieveTeamMemberDatabaseRecords.$return_value.results;
    const match = rows.find((r) => r.properties.email?.email === steps.trigger.event.body.email);
    if (!match) return $.flow.exit("no matching team member");
    return {
      userName: match.properties.name.title[0].plain_text,
      managerEmail: match.properties.manager.people[0]?.person.email,
    };
  },
});
```

### Pattern: build payload for a downstream prebuilt action

```js
// buildEmailContent.js  (output consumed by sendEmailToEmployee_action.json)
export default defineComponent({
  async run({ steps, $ }) {
    return {
      emailSubject: `Your request was submitted`,
      emailBody: `<html>…${steps.retrieveTeamMember.$return_value.userName}…</html>`,
    };
  },
});
```

The matching `sendEmailToEmployee_action.json` references this via:

```json
{
  "savedComponent": { "key": "gmail-send-email" },
  "configuredProps": {
    "gmail": "$auths.gmail",
    "to": "{{steps.trigger.event.body.email}}",
    "subject": "{{steps.buildEmailContent.$return_value.emailSubject}}",
    "bodyHtml": "{{steps.buildEmailContent.$return_value.emailBody}}"
  }
}
```

### Pattern: HTTP trigger that responds synchronously

```js
async run({ steps, $ }) {
  // ...do work...
  await $.respond({ status: 200, body: { ok: true, ref: result.id } });
}
```

### Pattern: idempotency for retried polling

```js
async run({ steps, $ }) {
  const seen = (await $.service.db.get("seen_ids")) || [];
  const fresh = items.filter((i) => !seen.includes(i.id));
  if (!fresh.length) return $.flow.exit("nothing new");
  await $.service.db.set("seen_ids", [...seen.slice(-500), ...fresh.map((i) => i.id)]);
  return { fresh };
}
```

## Scaffolding a NEW workflow

**YOU (the AI) should perform this step.** When asked to create a new workflow:

1.  **Run the helper script** in the terminal to scaffold the folder structure and JSON definition:
    ```bash
    npm run create -- \
      --project <ProjectName> \
      --name <WorkflowName> \
      --trigger <http|timer|email> \
      --steps <comma,separated,step,names>
    ```
2.  **Inspect existing workflows** in `exported_workflows/` to match the coding style, prop naming, and error handling patterns of the project.
3.  **Fill in the logic** for the generated `.js` stubs using the `defineComponent` contract described above.

**Getting it into Pipedream (manual — there is no API path):**

The Pipedream public REST API can create empty workflow shells but cannot populate triggers, steps, or code. There is also no "Import from JSON" UI feature. You — or the user — have to build the workflow once in the UI and paste each `.js` file's contents into a code cell.

Walk the user through this exact sequence after you scaffold:

1. Open https://pipedream.com → pick the target project → **New workflow**.
2. Add a trigger that matches `triggers[0].type` from `workflow_definition.json` (e.g. **HTTP / Webhook** for `HttpInterface`, **Schedule** for `Timer`).
3. For each entry in `steps[]` (in `order`), click `+` → **Run custom code** (Node.js), name the cell to match the step's `namespace`, then copy-paste the contents of `<stepName>.js` into the editor. For prebuilt action steps (`<step>_action.json`), pick the matching component (e.g. `slack-send-message-to-channel`) from the action picker and copy the `configuredProps` field-by-field.
4. Connect any apps the steps reference in `props` (e.g. `{ type: "app", app: "notion" }` → connect the Notion account when prompted).
5. Click **Deploy** in the workflow editor.

Once the workflow is built once, future copies of the *same shape* can be cloned via the share-link path (`⋯ → Create Share Link` → `tch_xxx` → `POST /v1/workflows` with `template_id`). That's the only programmatic deploy that actually carries content.

## Authoring checklist (run mentally before declaring done)

- [ ] Exactly **one** entry in `triggers[]` and its `type` is set.
- [ ] Every step has a unique `name`/`namespace` (matches the basename of its `.js` file).
- [ ] `defineComponent({ props, run })` is the default export of every code-cell.
- [ ] `props` declares EVERY external dependency the step uses (`{type:"app",app:"..."}` for OAuth; typed props for user input). No bare environment access.
- [ ] No `console.log` left in production-style steps — use `$.export("debug", …)` instead so logs are searchable.
- [ ] HTTP-trigger workflows call `$.respond(...)` exactly once OR rely on Pipedream's default 200 (don't mix).
- [ ] Polling/cron steps are idempotent (use `$.service.db` cursors).
- [ ] If migrating OFF Pipedream eventually: list the `$.flow.*` and `$.send.*` calls used — they're the surface area the self-host runtime needs to emulate.

## Don't

- Don't import `axios` from a relative path — Pipedream provides it globally; just `import axios from "axios"` works in code-cells.
- Don't `process.exit()` — use `$.flow.exit()`.
- Don't pass secrets via props' `default` — use `{type:"app",app:"..."}` and connect the account in the UI.
- Don't return Promises from `run()` without `await` — the run finishes before the promise resolves and you'll lose state.

